<br>
  Tree branches breaking across his legs like long matchsticks.<br>
<br>
  Punctures and gashes over his torso and limbs from the sharp protrusions in the ancient living things.<br>
<br>
  He felt a passing envy of the living trees.<br>
<br>
  Un-death so much like the eternal itch that can never quite be scratched <br>
<br>
  “Let them Rot in it!”<br>
<br>
  The raging sweep of his arm knocks over trees like stalks of wheat.<br>
<br>
  “She was ended by the very creatures I helped create.” He raged at some unknown source.<br>
<br>
  The blind fury drives him onward as the blood tears washing down his face blurred his vision.  A very thick old tree sent him spinning and now running in a different direction.<br>
<br>
  The scent of other supernatural beings wafts through the air, but any further interest in this world fades as the last grasp on reality is finally released. Understanding of liberation from this world slowly brings a previously unknown peace.<br>
<br>
  And then the words of poetry came back through from Thomas’ lost memories.<br>
<br>
&gt;   I stepped into an avalanche,<br>
      It covered up my soul.<br>
  When I am not this hunchback that you see,<br>
      I sleep beneath the golden hill.<br>
  You who wish to conquer pain,<br>
      You must learn, learn to serve me well.<br>
<br>
  You strike my side by accident,<br>
      As you go down for your gold.<br>
  The cripple here that you clothe and feed,<br>
      Is neither starved nor cold.<br>
  He does not ask for your company<br>
      Not at the center, the center of the world.<br>
<br>
  When I am on a pedestal, <br>
      You did not raise me there<br>
  Your laws do not compel me now<br>
      To kneel grotesque and bare<br>
  I, myself, am the pedestal<br>
      For this ugly hump at which you stare.<br>
<br>
  You who wish to conquer pain<br>
      You must learn what makes me kind.<br>
  The crumbs of love that you offer me,<br>
      They’re the crumbs I’ve left behind.<br>
  Your pain is no credential here<br>
      It’s just the shadow, a shadow of my wound.<br>
<br>
  I have begun to long for you,<br>
      I, who have no greed.<br>
  I have begun to ask for you,<br>
      I, who have no need.<br>
  You say you’ve gone away from me,<br>
      But I can feel you, I feel it when you breathe.<br>
<br>
  Do not dress in those rags for me,<br>
      I know you are not poor<br>
  And don’t love me quite so fiercely now<br>
      When you know that you are not sure<br>
  It is your turn beloved,<br>
      It is your flesh that I wear<br>
<br>
-<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
-<br>
<br>
  The eastern horizon gathers the faint highlight of impending sunrise and Jack can feel the call to slumber as his supernaturally chilled body cools the boulder upon which he is perched. He waits in his slowed tears and abandon to see the glorious sun once more: His eternal release.<br>
  As the dew falls he hears the movement of another creature up the hillside, coming toward him, making its approach known.<br>
  Jack remains unmoving and disinterested while the Werewolf steps out from the underbrush and cautiously approaches Jack’s unearthly Horrid form. The Werewolf realizes this intruder’s awareness by the telltale tracking of its monstrous ears, but is confused by its total lack of interest.<br>
  Realizing that this was no trap, the Werewolf sat near Jack and observed him, waiting to see what he’d do or say before destroying this intruder. Jack’s eyes were glued upon the eastern sky and remained so, unwaveringly.<br>
<br>
  Finally as the rising light begins to clearly affect the intruder, the Werewolf speaks in an old and wise tone, “This was your best option?”<br>
<br>
  Very faintly, Jack whispers, “yes.”<br>
<br>
  “I have smelled you here, before, you know. You used to sleep near here in the daylight in the back of your car.   …I miss watching your companion roll in the field and clean himself in the sun as you slept. He always reminded me of my youth.”<br>
<br>
  “Yeah, he was beautiful…  …they killed him too.” Jack forced the words through renewed tears. His despair and sorrow made his soul welcome the painful light that began to burn his eyes and make his skin feel as though it was boiling.<br>
<br>
  “You know I’m supposed to kill you for your intrusion into my territory; especially because I’m their elder and you’re the enemy, don’t you.”<br>
<br>
  “Yes, I know.” The tears washed over his face, “I don’t mind. Do so if you like.”<br>
<br>
“Well, …the sun is almost up and I just don’t think there’d be much point in it.” The Werewolf gave a surprisingly compassionate, if terribly toothy smile.<br>
<br>
“I would be a less than satisfying kill…”, Jack spoke with a painful smile through his blood-tear washed face. He mournfully looked the ancient werewolf in the eyes and asked finally asked the stranger, “Stay with me to watch the sun rise?”<br>
<br>
“Yeah, why not? …I’ll bet you haven’t seen one in a while.”<br>
