She would have expected as much from the majority of the population of the City.  They had ignored her warnings of Sabbat, if those who had been told had even bothered to pass on that information.  And for all their protests of organization skill and power, they were still children, and when faced with someone of as much self assurance and self possession as the Hunter, well they were bound to simply step aside.  She had not really expected any of them to care.  To make a stand.  After all, she had been made aware that they had indeed seen her before, and no one had made an effort to seek her out possitively or negatively until the Tremere had accidentally found her while seeking Demon worshippers.<br>
She had a moment to decide whether going after Jack was what she should do.  She could probably just catch him.  Somehow tho she felt that he'd have a better chance without her.<br>
She stepped onto the wind and surfed it back to the Chantry.  Her own rage was building.  She hovered above the false sanctuary and remembered all the good words, the big words, descriptive sharp and precise, that she had not used in so long, so long alone.<br>
Her mouth opened, and she had no idea if those were actually the words that poured forth, or if she drew only on animal howls of despair.<br>
&quot;HELP US!  I have done everything you asked.  Jack served you.  The girls served you.  Thomas served you.  You have done nothing but gain from my family.  HELP US!  You swore, all of you, that your walls would stand against whatever Sabbat that came.  You swore that I'd be safe here.  I would have given you everything, just to pretend for awhile that Jack was Thomas, that the girls were Thomas.  Just to pretend for awhile.  I have done *nothing* wrong.  YOU PROMISED.  I want everyone to hear what your word is worth.  NOTHING.  Not even the breath it's born on.  YOU BASTARDS.  What would it cost you?  To live up to your word?  To meet your promises?  BASTARDS BASTARDS BASTARDS.  I wish I was one of the damned Demon worshippers you sought.  I'd call on it to haunt you.  I'd sell my soul to make sure none of you know a moments peace, none of you ever feel love or trust or loyalty.  May you all be cursed forever to be as still and cold and unmoved as the stones here.&quot; <br>
Below her, the Gargoyles shifted, listening to some silent command.  She saw the flashes of personality and individuality that most others did not bother to notice.  Some leapt to the air with a joy to serve.  Some hesitated in confusion.  Some took flight with sad compassion.  They soared up to her.  She flexed her own wings, tearing them through her hooded shirt and shaking them free, to help her climb away.  <br>
Some of these were Thomas' children, some the girls', Jack's.  They flew and dived trying to catch her with dogged tenacity.  One she brushed as he past, and it's wings atrophied at her command.  It plummeted to the ground.  Another almost caught her and she twisted away, mangling it's hand as she ripped free.  There were too many of them.  Their strong bat wings buffeted the air, creating turbulance that she could not ride.  She shot up, pressing her little used wings to service.  Desperately she tried to modify them as she flew, make them into something that would set her free.<br>
Suddenly the pressure dropped from under her.  She had overshot the rising currents.  She had been holding too much mass to interact with all the others, and she had misjudged. Her wings lashed out trying to find some purchase on the failing updraft.  They whipped around her tumbling her out of the sky as surely as if her wings were sun melted wax.  <br>
She looked up and watched the stars rush away from her.  The same stars that she and Thomas had counted and wished on years ago.<br>
With a defiant effort she flipped herself, to face the oncoming cloud of Gargoyles.  She met them tooth fist and claw, laughing sadly at the end.  She felt one of her wings wrenched loose, torn meatily from the socket.  With her last bit of strength she flung a message to the wind.  <br>
&quot;Good Bye&quot;<br>
She stopped fighting.<br>
The gargoyle who caught her falling body snapped her neck.  It startled when she still moved anyway, stretching to kiss the beast on it's pebbly cheek.  She knew grace, she had felt true love, she would find Thomas somewhere.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=theherald@scbnforum58570>The Herald</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Clan Malkavian</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/25/03 11:03:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=84.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Comments..</span><hr size=1> A far more poetic death than inches from a nearby car, neh?<br>
